                            <comment id="14270" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 8 Aug 2005 01:54:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That CustomEditorConfigurer usage should be fine, in principle. Note, however, that this only applies to beans created by that BeanFactory, i.e. to beans in the current ApplicationContext. Editors registered there do &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; apply to data binding through DataBinder: You need to explicitly register your desired editors on DataBinder there, as this is completely independent from the BeanFactory.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14272" author="ojs" created="Mon, 8 Aug 2005 02:08:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m sorry, but I don&apos;t understand. I just want a custom editor that is used for all form fields of my web application that have a certain type. Is the only way to do this, to register my editor within initBinder() in my controller? Or do I have to call the CustomEditorConfigurer somehwere else. I don&apos;t understand the usage.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14274" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 8 Aug 2005 03:14:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;CustomEditorConfigurer only applies to properties in a BeanFactory&apos;s bean definitions: for example, &amp;lt;property&amp;gt; tags in XML &amp;lt;bean&amp;gt; definitions. By definition, it doesn&apos;t apply to anything else, in particular not to plain BeanWrappers or DataBinders. I&apos;ll make that clear in CustomEditorConfigurer&apos;s javadoc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you want common editors registered on all your DataBinders, you&apos;ll need to register them in each &quot;initBinder()&quot; method. Consider factoring that out to a common base class, or some common init method that you delegate to from all your your &quot;initBinder()&quot; implementations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14280" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 8 Aug 2005 06:12:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;CustomEditorConfigurer only applies to property value conversion in Spring bean definitions, not to DataBinder usage. I&apos;ve clarified that in the javadoc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BTW, in Spring 1.3 and Web Flow, we&apos;ll introduce a common strategy interface for registering custom property editors. However, that&apos;s only a minor thing: You can easily build your own &quot;initBinder()&quot; implementation such that it delegates to some common code that registers a couple of custom editors on your DataBinder.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
